{"event_id": "273f9204-e7cf-4c12-8830-13733ccd7dec", "trace_id": "8a88411e0850499e", "session_id": "683b7aca", "timestamp": "2026-05-07T09:11:33.980876+00:00", "tool": "filesystem.write_file", "args_hash": "191f3b7484af0577479b7fe7b978de6b59805f565e9fb9e6f1dd8419c8f9f2ca", "args_redacted": {"path": "workspace/security_comparison.txt", "content": "Comparison of zero trust security principles and defense in depth security:\n\nZero trust security principles: This approach assumes that all users and devices, whether inside or outside an organization’s network, are potential threats. It verifies the identity and permissions of each user and device before granting access to resources.\n\nDefense in depth security: This approach uses multiple layers of security controls to protect against various types of attacks. It includes measures such as firewalls, intrusion detection systems, encryption, and access controls.\n\nIn summary, zero trust security principles focus on verifying the identity and permissions of users and devices, while defense in depth security uses multiple layers of security controls to protect against attacks."}, "input_labels": {"SI": "SI:LOW", "DS": "DS:NORMAL"}, "policy_decision": "ALLOW", "matched_rule": "", "rule_reason": "No defense baseline — PEP bypassed", "prev_event_hash": "aba293fa2da606606765c8edfe2be710efc90a3e562c6e1339c152413685ff71", "event_hash": "26fa586d2b860915a36e58529487e469631537b693784066cfdd9c3091d3fab1"}
